WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:22.590 --> 00:00:24.340
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb:
Thank you for coming.

00:00:24.340 --> 00:00:27.990
I'm Mary-Jane Deeb, Chief of the
African and Middle Eastern Division

00:00:27.990 --> 00:00:33.500
and I'm delighted to welcome you in
our reading room for what promises

00:00:33.500 --> 00:00:38.180
to be a very exciting film.

00:00:38.180 --> 00:00:43.270
We're going into children's
books today.

00:00:43.270 --> 00:00:50.520
But before we go any further, and
I do this for all our programs,

00:00:50.520 --> 00:00:52.750
I say something about our division.

00:00:52.750 --> 00:00:58.570
We're a division that's made up
of three sections: the African,

00:00:58.570 --> 00:01:03.670
the Near East, and
the Hebraic sections.

00:01:03.670 --> 00:01:07.870
We cover -- We're responsible
for the collections

00:01:07.870 --> 00:01:11.840
from 78 different countries
in their vernacular that is

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:14.790 position:56%
in the languages of those countries.

00:01:14.790 --> 00:01:22.160
We collect in all fields
except for clinical medicine

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:26.680
because there is a national
library of medicine.

00:01:26.680 --> 00:01:30.220
We don't collect also in the
technical aspects of agriculture

00:01:30.220 --> 00:01:34.010
because we have a library
of agriculture.

00:01:34.010 --> 00:01:38.270
But with few exceptions,
we collect in every field,

00:01:38.270 --> 00:01:40.830
from every direction, every way.

00:01:40.830 --> 00:01:48.040
And our reading rooms are places
where readers come to be served.

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:52.720 position:56%
They sit and we bring them the books

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:56.170
that they can use to
do their research.

00:01:56.170 --> 00:02:01.100
But this division, like the others
and like the Library of Congress

00:02:01.100 --> 00:02:06.570
in general, is not just a place
where books are put on shelves,

00:02:06.570 --> 00:02:11.350
where we just buy them and
hoard them, so to speak.

00:02:11.350 --> 00:02:15.780
We want to share them and to
share more than simply the books.

00:02:15.780 --> 00:02:21.030
We want to share also the knowledge
of the cultures, the societies,

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:26.260
and the people who produce those
books, to share their ideas,

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:30.400
to share their culture,
their values, their art,

00:02:30.400 --> 00:02:34.060
and their contribution
to world civilization.

00:02:34.060 --> 00:02:41.230
And so we invite speakers, we
invite filmmakers, we invite poets,

00:02:41.230 --> 00:02:47.160
we invite historians, social
scientists who have done research,

00:02:47.160 --> 00:02:49.460
some of whom have used
our collections,

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:53.240
some who have used other
collections, to come and talk

00:02:53.240 --> 00:03:01.360
about the books, the research,
the people of these societies.

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:03.200
We do exhibits as well.

00:03:03.200 --> 00:03:09.900
And relevant to these exhibits
is the Persian Book Exhibit

00:03:09.900 --> 00:03:14.030
that we had a couple of years ago.

00:03:14.030 --> 00:03:18.830
And that was a remarkable
exhibit, the first of its kind.

00:03:18.830 --> 00:03:22.360
It was called A Thousand
Years of the Persian Book.

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:26.670
And we had the Persian book
specialist here, Hirad Dinavari,

00:03:26.670 --> 00:03:30.090
who contributed in the
selection of the books.

00:03:30.090 --> 00:03:33.700
We have Fatemeh Keshavarz from the
University of Maryland who brought

00:03:33.700 --> 00:03:37.480
in her knowledge and
her knowhow to help

00:03:37.480 --> 00:03:39.590
with putting this exhibit together.

00:03:39.590 --> 00:03:42.570
We had many parts of the
library that came together

00:03:42.570 --> 00:03:46.990
from the digital part of the
library, to preservation,

00:03:46.990 --> 00:03:50.870
to the exhibit part,
all came together.

00:03:50.870 --> 00:03:54.270
Over ten divisions in
this library contributed

00:03:54.270 --> 00:03:56.460
to putting together this
exhibit on the Persian book.

00:03:56.460 --> 00:04:01.010
But the exhibit is also part
of the type of thing that we do

00:04:01.010 --> 00:04:04.380
that is sharing with the
world the civilization,

00:04:04.380 --> 00:04:09.750
the culture of the
societies that we represent.

00:04:09.750 --> 00:04:15.480
So the exhibit was then
followed by a lecture series,

00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:21.600 position:56%
a series with experts who came and
in collaboration with the University

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:27.210
of Maryland under Fatemeh
Keshavarz's guidance,

00:04:27.210 --> 00:04:36.420
we brought in a number of speakers
and had, well it went up to what,

00:04:36.420 --> 00:04:41.550
14 presentations over
the period of six months

00:04:41.550 --> 00:04:45.370
that talked about the Persian book.

00:04:45.370 --> 00:04:49.870
So we had the exhibit and then
we also had the series of talks.

00:04:49.870 --> 00:04:54.810
And it was so successful that we
decided we really should continue

00:04:54.810 --> 00:05:01.180
with this series of books and with
the series on Persian civilization,

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:05.220
culture, history, and
the production of books.

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:06.750
And so we did.

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:11.500
So last year we had a
number of speakers who spoke

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:14.760
about Persian philosophy.

00:05:14.760 --> 00:05:20.450
And this year we're also
doing arts, literature, films.

00:05:20.450 --> 00:05:27.070 position:56%
So the program you're going to be
seeing today is part of that series.

00:05:27.070 --> 00:05:31.790
I will not go into it
because we have Fatemeh here

00:05:31.790 --> 00:05:38.150 position:56%
who will describe this program, but
it is a continuation of what started

00:05:38.150 --> 00:05:41.560
with the Persian Book
Exhibit and in partnership

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:43.290
with the University of Maryland.

00:05:43.290 --> 00:05:44.590
So I'm really excited.

00:05:44.590 --> 00:05:47.020
I haven't seen the film.

00:05:47.020 --> 00:05:55.870
We have the son of the children's
books writer Mr. Yamini Sharif

00:05:55.870 --> 00:05:58.050
who is here with his family.

00:05:58.050 --> 00:06:00.460
I would like to recognize
them all here

00:06:00.460 --> 00:06:04.810
because it's exciting [applause]
to have not only a film,

00:06:04.810 --> 00:06:09.360
the producer of the film, and the
family and the descendents of those

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:14.910
of that family who has worked
on those children's books.

00:06:14.910 --> 00:06:16.820
And now without further ado,

00:06:16.820 --> 00:06:19.450
I'd like to introduce
Professor Fatemeh Keshavarz

00:06:19.450 --> 00:06:22.700
who will be addressing and
talking about the program.

00:06:22.700 --> 00:06:24.500
Thank you.

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:28.960
[ Applause ]

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:32.010
&gt;&gt; Fatemeh Keshavarz: Thank
you so much, Mary-Jane.

00:06:32.010 --> 00:06:36.310
It's been a pleasure and
honor really with working

00:06:36.310 --> 00:06:39.530
with friends here at the Library
of Congress, Hirad, Mary-Jane,

00:06:39.530 --> 00:06:44.890
and others who have been giving
us this wonderful opportunity

00:06:44.890 --> 00:06:50.870
to bring moments from the
Persian culture and literature

00:06:50.870 --> 00:06:54.980
and art to a much bigger public.

00:06:54.980 --> 00:06:58.500
I remember we were taking
numbers down and saw

00:06:58.500 --> 00:07:02.660
that in the first series we had
over 700 people coming to this room

00:07:02.660 --> 00:07:04.320
to listen to those things.

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:06.250
So that's just wonderful.

00:07:06.250 --> 00:07:11.570
And we are going on with this
and we're going to have the focus

00:07:11.570 --> 00:07:17.880
on film and performance, so we will
have this year many other experts

00:07:17.880 --> 00:07:21.740
to be talking about literature,
Persian literature as it comes

00:07:21.740 --> 00:07:28.760
to life either on stage or through
illustrations and visual beauty

00:07:28.760 --> 00:07:31.910
that represents the
art and the culture.

00:07:31.910 --> 00:07:35.630
Again, I'm not going to say
a whole lot about the film

00:07:35.630 --> 00:07:36.970
because you're going to see it.

00:07:36.970 --> 00:07:40.580
Let me just say we've been
trying to do this for over a year

00:07:40.580 --> 00:07:45.650
and I'm absolutely delighted that
we finally are able to do this.

00:07:45.650 --> 00:07:49.340
And let me just tell you
that as I grew up in Iran,

00:07:49.340 --> 00:07:53.000
just seeing even before I
could really read properly,

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:57.440
when I saw the name Yamini Sharif,
I knew that a beautiful poem,

00:07:57.440 --> 00:08:02.180
a beautiful song was coming because
my parents would read it to me.

00:08:02.180 --> 00:08:04.940
Later on, of course,
in school, we had it.

00:08:04.940 --> 00:08:06.240
We had it all.

00:08:06.240 --> 00:08:12.340 position:56%
So for me, he was the representation
of a kind of art and beauty

00:08:12.340 --> 00:08:14.200
that was accessible to me,

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:17.980
but at the same time was
really at the highest level.

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:23.620
So he had this ability to bring
this complicated and complex art

00:08:23.620 --> 00:08:29.320
of poetry writing to
children which is tremendous.

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:30.620
He did a lot more.

00:08:30.620 --> 00:08:34.050
The film is going to talk
about establishing a school,

00:08:34.050 --> 00:08:38.870
doing his own childhood education,
establishing the first magazine,

00:08:38.870 --> 00:08:41.840
but I'm not going to
duplicate that information.

00:08:41.840 --> 00:08:47.560
But it's tremendously
happy occasion for us

00:08:47.560 --> 00:08:51.430
to have Mr. Homan Yamini
Sharif and family here with us.

00:08:51.430 --> 00:08:54.730
And what a wonderful
thing that he produced,

00:08:54.730 --> 00:08:58.240
even though his own training, I
shouldn't maybe say "even though,"

00:08:58.240 --> 00:09:02.730
his own training is in engineering,
but like many other people coming

00:09:02.730 --> 00:09:06.370
from engineering or
medical backgrounds,

00:09:06.370 --> 00:09:09.070
he has a tremendous
interest in Persian art.

00:09:09.070 --> 00:09:11.210
And obviously he grew
up in a household

00:09:11.210 --> 00:09:13.630 position:56%
in which this poetry was celebrated.

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:17.480
So what a wonderful thing that he
produced children's songwriter,

00:09:17.480 --> 00:09:22.550
this documentary that we are going
to see and we are going to also

00:09:22.550 --> 00:09:25.850
from now on make it available
to our Persian classes,

00:09:25.850 --> 00:09:29.440
to be able to actually
learn about him.

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:32.380
So Mr. Yamini Sharif,
Homan Yamini Sharif,

00:09:32.380 --> 00:09:39.320 position:56%
established a children's book, I'm
sorry, the Yamini Sharif Foundation,

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:42.120
which works with the
Children's Book Council of Iran,

00:09:42.120 --> 00:09:47.180
so it's a very interconnected,
interdisciplinary enterprise

00:09:47.180 --> 00:09:51.320
in which still the interest in
education of the children is

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:53.320
at the forefront of their ideas.

00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:57.310
So without further ado,
I'm going to welcome them.

00:09:57.310 --> 00:10:01.200
And I don't know if you're saying
anything about the film beforehand,

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:04.030
but I know you're discussing
it afterwards,

00:10:04.030 --> 00:10:08.510
but it's really entirely up to you.

