00:11:01.950 --> 00:11:05.350
I will very briefly talk a
little bit about how we came

00:11:05.350 --> 00:11:06.650
out to make this documentary.

00:11:06.650 --> 00:11:11.750
The documentary itself goes
through the history and how this,

00:11:11.750 --> 00:11:16.010 position:56%
my father was interested and how the
children literature was developed

00:11:16.010 --> 00:11:21.390
in Iran, which my father played
a very major role in that.

00:11:21.390 --> 00:11:25.790
But to make it short, I, as a
child, was very fond of my father.

00:11:25.790 --> 00:11:29.740 position:56%
So I used to listen to him a lot and
he would tell me about his childhood

00:11:29.740 --> 00:11:33.530
and his interests and very
difficult childhood that he had

00:11:33.530 --> 00:11:35.220
and you'll see in the film.

00:11:35.220 --> 00:11:40.330
And I learned a lot about his life
and his education and how he came

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:44.060
to become interested in children's
literature and got involved

00:11:44.060 --> 00:11:47.850
in writing and magazines and so on.

00:11:47.850 --> 00:11:55.850
At the same time I was also a
subject of what he was doing.

00:11:55.850 --> 00:11:58.050
I was audience as well
because I was right

00:11:58.050 --> 00:12:00.540
at the age that he was writing for.

00:12:00.540 --> 00:12:04.740
So when the Kayhan Bacheha,
which everybody knows here,

00:12:04.740 --> 00:12:09.610
when it came out, started, my
father started with another

00:12:09.610 --> 00:12:13.610
of his colleagues, I
started reading that.

00:12:13.610 --> 00:12:18.550
I read the first textbook
that was written by my father

00:12:18.550 --> 00:12:22.490
as a national textbook
for the first graders.

00:12:22.490 --> 00:12:26.170
So I read that and so
on until I read it --

00:12:26.170 --> 00:12:30.360
So I became very familiar
with the poetry in his works

00:12:30.360 --> 00:12:35.830
and how he developed and all
the chronology of it as well.

00:12:35.830 --> 00:12:40.770
Then as I grew up and I went
to high school and I realized

00:12:40.770 --> 00:12:45.710
that his fame is just growing
in Iran and everybody knew him,

00:12:45.710 --> 00:12:51.350 position:56%
which was kind of natural to me, but
then after I came to United States

00:12:51.350 --> 00:12:53.910
as a student, went
back, worked there,

00:12:53.910 --> 00:12:57.150
and I saw that this has
become a more than normal.

00:12:57.150 --> 00:13:01.530
He had -- Because of generation
that read the textbooks and went

00:13:01.530 --> 00:13:05.930
to school that he established
with my mother and all the books

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:10.050
and different things and magazines,
so and that became very interesting

00:13:10.050 --> 00:13:15.350
for me because that there
was somebody that started

00:13:15.350 --> 00:13:21.080
from even not zero, negative,
as you will see in this film,

00:13:21.080 --> 00:13:24.940
with no support, not only no
support but all the hurdles

00:13:24.940 --> 00:13:27.670
that you can think of
in front of somebody,

00:13:27.670 --> 00:13:30.280
going back about 80
years ago in Iran

00:13:30.280 --> 00:13:35.000
when children were really not
even counted as human beings.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:38.350 position:56%
They were just in a transition
period, a waiting period to grow up.

00:13:38.350 --> 00:13:40.360
That's all it was, to grow up

00:13:40.360 --> 00:13:44.730
and just take some burden off
the shoulders of the parents.

00:13:44.730 --> 00:13:49.530
So it was very interesting that
that person, without any support,

00:13:49.530 --> 00:13:54.160
could come and become somebody who
could really play this major role

00:13:54.160 --> 00:13:55.920
in the children's literature
and became very famous.

00:13:55.920 --> 00:13:59.490
So that by itself was
very interesting.

00:13:59.490 --> 00:14:02.400
And Iran is a difficult
environment for the people

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:04.490
that they don't have any support.

00:14:04.490 --> 00:14:08.140 position:56%
So you have somebody that can come
up with this very interesting story,

00:14:08.140 --> 00:14:11.630
that's why I thought I would
like to make that documentary

00:14:11.630 --> 00:14:13.780
and then we thought about it.

00:14:13.780 --> 00:14:15.790
The environment in Iran
at that time was not --

00:14:15.790 --> 00:14:18.140
But recently, because
documentaries are very popular,

00:14:18.140 --> 00:14:21.070
it became easier to make it.

00:14:21.070 --> 00:14:26.390
So and at the same time,
Children's Book Council

00:14:26.390 --> 00:14:30.810
of Iran a few years ago
had a tribute to my father

00:14:30.810 --> 00:14:32.460
and that also was very interesting.

00:14:32.460 --> 00:14:36.690
From that tribute came
a major article

00:14:36.690 --> 00:14:42.570
in Iranian newspaper [inaudible]
and the person who wrote

00:14:42.570 --> 00:14:46.600
that article was the person who
later on became the director

00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:50.640
of the film, Mr. Hooman Zarif.

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:55.180
And he actually called me a few
years after we had that tribute

00:14:55.180 --> 00:14:57.510
and now I'm thinking for years
to make this documentary.

00:14:57.510 --> 00:14:58.810
He called me and said, "I want

00:14:58.810 --> 00:15:00.740
to make a documentary
about your father."

00:15:00.740 --> 00:15:02.040
And I said.

00:15:02.040 --> 00:15:03.340
"That's pretty good."

00:15:03.340 --> 00:15:04.640
And he wanted me to support.

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:06.380
I said, "Well, you have full
support but what do you know

00:15:06.380 --> 00:15:08.040
about documentary,
you're a journalist?"

00:15:08.040 --> 00:15:13.550
He said he just made a documentary
about another person who was known

00:15:13.550 --> 00:15:21.310
to Iran, Hossein Gol-e-Golab,
