01:30:14.380 --> 01:30:21.000
&gt;&gt; Can you just tell us how long
it took to put the film together?

01:30:21.000 --> 01:30:22.890
&gt;&gt; Homan Yamini Sharif:
Well, it took about two years

01:30:22.890 --> 01:30:27.880 position:56%
and the reason it took this long was
it had to be done during the trips

01:30:27.880 --> 01:30:34.210 position:56%
to Iran and getting all these people
together and finding time for them,

01:30:34.210 --> 01:30:36.990
the different conditions they
were enduring took some time.

01:30:36.990 --> 01:30:45.080 position:56%
Also, it was difficult to edit and
I had to be present for the edition,

01:30:45.080 --> 01:30:46.380
because for the chronology

01:30:46.380 --> 01:30:51.120
and all different relative
subjects had to be taken care of.

01:30:51.120 --> 01:30:55.440 position:56%
We also we wanted to do more filming
but the conditions in Iran were

01:30:55.440 --> 01:31:00.090
in such a way that if you wanted to
film, you know, in public places,

01:31:00.090 --> 01:31:03.830
you had to go through certain
getting permission and all that

01:31:03.830 --> 01:31:08.740
and we did not really have the
time to do it and so we had to come

01:31:08.740 --> 01:31:11.390
with different creativity
to do this.

01:31:11.390 --> 01:31:12.790
&gt;&gt; I have a question.

01:31:12.790 --> 01:31:14.090
&gt;&gt; Go ahead.

01:31:14.090 --> 01:31:15.390
&gt;&gt; Just a brief one.

01:31:15.390 --> 01:31:16.850
When you are filming,
you are talking,

01:31:16.850 --> 01:31:21.260
you're in a beautiful
environment outside with the trees

01:31:21.260 --> 01:31:25.120
and then it rains, where
was it [inaudible]?

01:31:25.120 --> 01:31:28.110
&gt;&gt; Homan Yamini Sharif:
It was a house that was --

01:31:28.110 --> 01:31:33.830 position:56%
Ironically, it was very interesting,
the [inaudible] in Iran,

01:31:33.830 --> 01:31:36.910
the television, radio
and television,

01:31:36.910 --> 01:31:40.930
approached us when they heard that
we are filming this and they wanted

01:31:40.930 --> 01:31:43.590 position:56%
to get the license to make the film.

01:31:43.590 --> 01:31:46.660
But because they would make it the
way they wanted, I said, "Well,

01:31:46.660 --> 01:31:51.220
let me make it and then if you like
it, then we'll, you can use that."

01:31:51.220 --> 01:31:55.660
But they helped us and
said, "How can we help you?"

01:31:55.660 --> 01:31:59.090
It was very interesting
to have that cooperation.

01:31:59.090 --> 01:32:02.590
And one of the things they did
is they have different contracts

01:32:02.590 --> 01:32:03.890
with different places.

01:32:03.890 --> 01:32:05.190
When they want to film,
they can go there.

01:32:05.190 --> 01:32:06.490
They said, "What do you need?"

01:32:06.490 --> 01:32:09.170
I said, "We'd like to be in
an environment which looks

01:32:09.170 --> 01:32:11.080
like my father's childhood."

01:32:11.080 --> 01:32:12.380
So they arranged this.

01:32:12.380 --> 01:32:16.590
This is a village north of
Tehran, in [inaudible] area.

01:32:16.590 --> 01:32:22.630
So we went there and
we did the film.

01:32:22.630 --> 01:32:25.750 position:56%
&gt;&gt; So my question is for the footage
for the film, all the photographs

01:32:25.750 --> 01:32:28.450
and items, did you get
most of it from inside Iran

01:32:28.450 --> 01:32:34.620
or did you look elsewhere as well
and how much archives are there

01:32:34.620 --> 01:32:37.570
from people you interviewed
that they gave you

01:32:37.570 --> 01:32:40.470
or sharing their [inaudible]
with you?

01:32:40.470 --> 01:32:43.250
&gt;&gt; Homan Yamini Sharif: The
archives, all the documents

01:32:43.250 --> 01:32:46.050
and other film, pictures
and reviews and all

01:32:46.050 --> 01:32:48.190
that came from our own archives.

01:32:48.190 --> 01:32:52.510
My father had a very good archive
while he was alive collecting

01:32:52.510 --> 01:32:56.780
different books and magazine,
literature and his own books

01:32:56.780 --> 01:32:59.280 position:56%
and we preserved that and we kept it

01:32:59.280 --> 01:33:01.060
and we collected as
much as we could.

01:33:01.060 --> 01:33:04.660
So we have archives in the
Foundation and we used this.

01:33:04.660 --> 01:33:05.960
&gt;&gt; That's wonderful.

01:33:05.960 --> 01:33:09.720
&gt;&gt; And who is illustrator?

01:33:09.720 --> 01:33:12.450 position:56%
Did you father paint or your sister?

01:33:12.450 --> 01:33:14.010
&gt;&gt; Homan Yamini Sharif:
The illustrator that talked

01:33:14.010 --> 01:33:16.190
in the film was Parviz Kalantari.

01:33:16.190 --> 01:33:20.610
Parviz Kalantari is a well known
illustrator for children's books

01:33:20.610 --> 01:33:24.550
and he was also a close
friend of my father

01:33:24.550 --> 01:33:27.050
and illustrated several
books for him.

01:33:27.050 --> 01:33:30.250
He has won several
international awards for his work.

01:33:30.250 --> 01:33:35.010
And as I mentioned, it's one of the
unfortunate things that happened

01:33:35.010 --> 01:33:38.240
